{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bdbdad28-07e2-4344-a700-c709ff4d9a17","content":"Here's the correct attribute for each framework:\n\n| Framework | Attribute |\n|-----------|-----------|\n| **MSTest** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **xUnit** | `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` or `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]` |\n| **NUnit** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **TUnit** | `[Skip(\"reason\")]` |\n\n**Example usage:**\n\n```csharp\n// MSTest\n[TestMethod]\n[Ignore(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyMsTest() { }\n\n// xUnit\n[Fact(Skip = \"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyXunitTest() { }\n\n// NUnit\n[Test]\n[Ignore(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyNunitTest() { }\n\n// TUnit\n[Test]\n[Skip(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyTunitTest() { }\n```\n\nKey differences: xUnit embeds the skip reason directly in the `[Fact]`/`[Theory]` attribute rather than using a separate attribute. The other three all use a standalone attribute alongside `[Test]`/`[TestMethod]`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6fa12c25-9bfa-45a5-883e-9a840049e79c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about test-skipping attributes across four .NET test frameworks. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without tools.","outputTokens":333,"requestId":"0840:307F5D:8244B1C:9099EA9:69EAC2E6"},"id":"0c9dfd67-931a-4e5b-b4f6-fbb3f5ac93e2","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:10:05.586Z","parentId":"18124e77-1a90-44a5-b37c-a78de8fbc1eb"}
